##British sports officials have denied plans to take over the Games after the Tokyo olympics-related summit was cancelled

The new-crown pneumonia epidemic is on the rise in Japan, where the Tokyo Olympics, scheduled to kick off in July, are facing challenges.

Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga stressed at a press conference on February 21 that the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics would go ahead as planned. It was the fourth time since January 31 that the Tokyo Organizing Committee had announced that the Games would not be canceled.

He said that in the light of the spread of the new pneumonia, the Japanese government will earnestly advance the preparations for the Olympic and Paralympic Games and ensure that the Games are held in a safe and secure manner, and stressed that, "The International Olympic Committee believe we can handle it. " .

However, the current Tokyo Olympic Games in the early part of the related activities have been suspended.

The Japanese government decided on February 21st to cancel the "host town summit" for the Tokyo Olympics, local media reported, citing the spread of COVID-19 pneumonia in the country. It is reported that the event was scheduled to be held in Tokyo on February 22.

The host town summit is an exchange event that the Japanese government is preparing for the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics, which was supposed to bring together Japan's autonomous communities across the country to discuss exchanges with other countries during the Games. Now the Japanese government has had to cancel the summit.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said it was asking event organizers to re examine the need to hold the event as a gathering. Relevant documents point out that if participants need contact without sufficient distance, it will increase the risk of infection and call for vigilance.

"At this stage, it's not all going to stop. It's ultimately up to the organisers to decide whether or not to hold the event, " said Katsunobu Kato, a Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare official.

"We will look at the epidemic situation in Japan and send a message in the future, " he said of the high-profile Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics

Earlier, the Tokyo Organizing Committee had stressed that "the Tokyo Olympics will never be canceled, we do not have a plan B. "

Tokyo said it would take all possible measures to deal with the threat posed by the outbreak. These measures are focused on two main areas, one is to prevent infection within the Olympic organizing committee, so as not to hinder the preparation of the Olympic Games, and the other is to prevent infection during the Olympic Games for athletes, for possible infection to propose a response plan.

The Tokyo Summer Olympics and Paralympics are scheduled to take place between July 24-august 9 and August 25-september 6,2020, respectively.

On February 20th Shaun Bailey, the conservative mayoral candidate for London, declared that London would be ready to host the Games if the outbreak forced the games to be held elsewhere.

Edson Arantes do Nascimento wrote on social media, "I urge the International Olympic Committee to seriously consider that London is ready to host the Olympics if need be. We have the necessary facilities and experience, and if I am elected mayor and need help, I guarantee that London will be able to host a major sporting event again. "

"The [ Japanese ] government has no comment on overseas matters, " Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga told a news conference in response to Edson Arantes do Nascimento's remarks

Although London hosted the 2012 Summer Games and is well equipped with venue resources and experience, the International Olympic Committee responded that there was no reason to make temporary plans to cancel or relocate the Games.

Meanwhile, Rui'an, who's assistant director general for health emergencies, said it was too early to tell whether the Tokyo Games would be postponed or closed.

In London, Edson Arantes do Nascimento's comments were met with scepticism, with his comments being seen as campaigning for the mayoral election in London in May.

London has no plans to take over, a British sports official said, according to Reuters. "This is a candidate for mayor, not a British or London attitude. "

As of 2400 local time on February 20, there were 728 confirmed cases and three deaths, according to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare and local governments. Of these, 634 were confirmed aboard the Diamond Princess cruise ship in Yokohama.

In fact, Japan's sports community has been affected by the outbreak.

More than 30,000 Volkswagen runners who had signed up for the Tokyo marathon have been ruled out of the race. While there are no plans to cancel the tests scheduled for March, some teams have already pulled out due to concerns about the outbreak.

In the history of the Olympic Games, there is no precedent for cancellation of the Games because of public health events. It was cancelled only three times during the first World War and the Second World War, tokyo just hosted its first Olympics.

Now that Japan is about to host the Olympics again after 56 years, it remains to be seen whether the sporting extravaganza will be unveiled on time.
